title: Geeetech Prusa I3 Stepper Mounting Plate for Bowden Extruder

description.text:
This mounting plate allows you to attach a MK8 extruder stepper motor (for a Bowden Extruder) to the frame of a Geeetech I3 with an acrylic frame. My printer is a I3 Pro Dual Extruder, so I know for sure it fits that model and probably all of the I3s that were made with that frame.

Update 1/22/18 I added a new mounting plate that moves the stepper motor forward. This allows the X carriage to move higher without hitting the Bowen tube. The collars on the rods limit the carriage movement at the top of the frame. If the collars were smaller or ground down, the carriage will be limited only by the top of the frame. It's probably not the best placement, but it required the least redesign. The plate secures the stepper mounting frame to the printed plate with only two screws. The filament load lever MUST be opposite the screws, so pressing down on the lever causes the stepper motor to be forced down into the printed plate. It may work the other way, but probably not for very long before the plate cracks. It's tricky to figure how it mounts; look carefully at the photo.

Update 5/10/16 This plate limits the vertical travel to a bit more than 160 mm. The motors will have to move towards the front of the printer to move the Teflon tube away from the carriage to get more clear vertical travel. A project for later date, when there's a need.

With the extruder motors off the carriage, you can use a different hot end, and feed the filament using a Bowden Extruder scheme. In the photo for the new plate, I'm using the 2-to-1 Switching hot end (one of MY THINGS) This hardware can be used to switch between two filament colors.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa I3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2 or .3 layer 4 or 5 perimeters

Infill:

25% Honeycomb

Notes:

Print two of the plates if you are planning on a dual extruder. If you want the same side up on each, select a mirror image for the second copy. I printed this in PLA and .2 LH. The plate is surprisingly strong for only 3 mm thick with the settings above. There is minimal deflection of the plate when the filament release lever is moved, even without supporting the extruder. With the thickness of the plate as furnished in the drawings, most, if not all of the screws you need to mount the extruders might be available as left-overs in the hardware that Geeetech furnished with the printer.
You need a couple 19.5/20 mm M3 cap screws and three M4 6 mm cap screws.
You also need the sheet metal bracket that mounts between the stepper motor and the mounting plate. These are available from Geeetech, Aliexpress, and eBay.

You probably will want to replace the dual extruder bracket on the carriage with a mounting bracket for a single extruder. It is available from the same sources as above. You gain about 30 mm of usable bed in the X direction when you remove the dual extruder mounting plate.

The mounting plate will handle a left and right hand extruder without any modifications. If you have two of the same, then a small amount of material will have to be removed form the original acrylic top plate, or the plate will have to be made thicker to countersink the screws because of interference with stepper motor mounting bracket. If you are adapting a I3 Pro Dual, then extruder #2 mounts on the left side and #1 on the right (as you face the printer). The motors turn in opposite directions, so there is no choice about the mounting unless you modify the firmware or the plate.

If you use the mixing hot end like Geeetech uses, you also need a mounting plate between the hot end and the carriage bracket. Check out the mounting plate I made for the 2/1 extruder that is available now from many sources. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1496657

title: Minolta MC/MD to Canon EOS mount

description.text:
This is an adaptor for the Minolta MC/MD lenses so they can fit into Canon EOS DSLR cameras. The main difference between this and the commercially available solutions is that this design is made with the flange focal lenght in mind so you can accurately use the focus distances and even the infinity focus on the Minolta lenses.
This is a work in progress and I will continue updating it. Since I don't have a 3d printer of my own I have to take it to my local 3d printing facility so changes on this project may be a bit slow.

-Update: Mount MKII has a bigger external diameter in order to compensate for the ABS shrink issue. It didn't work as I expected but I uploaded it in case someone can learn from my mistakes.
After a little work with the rotary tool for sanding and adjusting the size of the flaps (?) it fits on the camera mount and I finally took my first pictures without holding the lens with my hands. Since I did not adjusted the internal diameter for shrinkage (And since my original design is flawed anyway) the Minolta lens do not fit as expected, giving it an aditional 3mm (or so) of flange, making it unable to focus objects beyond 120cm. Next time I will print on PLA to get rid of the shrink problem. On a side note: ABS plastic is way softer than I imagined.

description.text:
Simple racing quad frame with minimal components to print.

You will need to print

  • 4 arms
  • 6 risers (two types which you may chose, 50mm is the higher version for extra clearance)
  • 1 lower plate
  • 1 top plate

I would suggest using machine screws as a method of fitting the arms to the lower plate and then using nyloc nuts.

The top plate has been designed to accommodate a kk2.1 flight board, there is 2mm stand-offs already included in the print. The lower plate has stand-offs for a standard power distribution board.

The maximum motor diameter is 24mm, the arms where designed to take 250 size motors.

This build should fit onto a 200mm x 200mm build plate. The largest pieces are the plates which measure 60mm x 200mm x 4mm

~Update~

I have updated the arm design, after a few trials with my previous design I am not happy with how much they flex and also lack some form of ground clearance. I have rectified the design, landing legs have been added and also added a beading below to reduce the flex when under load. 'File name - armv2.stl'

Printer:

Kossel XL

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1-0.2mm

Infill:

60% +

Notes:

You shouldn't require any supports as long as your print can cope with minimal overhangs.

I've built quite a few different sized multirotors, this one takes a lot of different designs into one. There is plenty of options to route cables to keep it as clean as possible.

The arms are designed to break off in the centre if you have a crash to reduce the impact force, they are simple to print and easy to replace.

The framework is tough, this is to protect the vital electronics. The risers are 10mm thick to aid in rigidity throughout the length of the plates.

title: Dalek Energy Weapon (1:1 Scale)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I have been working on my 1:1 scale Dalek for a few years now.  One thing I never liked was how my hand made energy weapon came out. Now that I have a 3D printer, I decided to do an upgrade.  
This design, like the handmade version, used a plasma/lightning tube that I removed from a toy.  If you are working on your own Dalek, then you will need to replace that with a plastic tube or render a center rod for the part.  Also, I did not add the servo screw holes in the print.  I just added them with a drill after I made the part.  
Lastly, I used 1/4 plastic tubing for the cage.  I decided not to print those because the part would have been too large for my printer.  It was easier to use the tubing.  
It is by far the largest and most complex print I have done to date on my Mosaic printer.

If you are not familiar with paracordgalaxy.com I would suggest going to their sight to scope out what they have.
In particular, they have seven sizes(diameter and strength) that are smaller than 550 paracord. all of the way down to .75mm called Nano.
Another tip about paracordgalaxy is to make a small purchase first, because they will start to send you monthly emails with discount codes(usually 10% off) for future orders. They have an amazing inventory of colors, sizes, buckles, charms, accessories and instructional information for all level of corders from beginners to experienced individuals.
This is starting to sound like some kind of commercial..... I just like to point other crafters to sites that I find that I like.

I wanted something which would hold a PS3 and PS4 controller, and preferably a WII U. As such, I aimed for a lower bumper which was minimalist to suit all 3 forms.

You can play with the parameters here:

Note that only the first view should be printed - the second one is an alternative approach which is proving too fragile for use right now. The last 3 views are there to allow specific tuning of the constituent parts.

description.text:
I used 1/4-20 threaded rod and five wingnuts on the rod. I heated up the threaded rod with a torch and clamped the quick clamps over the threaded rod with binder clips and when they were cool I super glued the quick clamp to the binder clips. The quick clamps don't have a ton of grip so I only use one to help making spool changes quicker.

for the spools I used the bearings from some roller blade wheels I had laying around. You can get a pair of roller blades from a thrift store for about $8usd. There is typically a small spacer that goes between the roller blade bearing and the axle that is necessary to fit on the 1/4-20 threaded rod.

title: Gym Towel Rail Bracket and Spray Bottle Shelf for the gym

description.text:
I recently bought a roll of those blue paper towels for the gym equipment in the garage, and a spray bottle of disinfectant. The hope is that the kids will use it when they've done their work out!

To avoid them getting lost or looking untidy, I thought I needed to 3D print a way of holding them. Hence these two objects.

There is a bracket which you will need two of, and a wooden pole not greater than 20mm diameter to hang between them. This goes through the middle of your roll of paper towels.

The shelf is fairly self explanatory. Holes in the top partly to speed printing, but also to all for draining if the bottle gets wet.
